Dear Lauren,

I have cc-ed here the major HARPS-N people involved with TOI-561 (Giampaolo and Luca) and our HARPS-N President (Stéphane).

Title: The TESS Keck Survey I: Masses, Densities, and Orbits of Three Sub-Neptune Sized Transiting Planets in TOI-561
Authors: Lauren M. Weiss, Fei Dai, the TESS Keck Survey, and others

Abstract: Systems with multiple transiting planets provide excellent natural laboratories for testing the physics of planet formation, since the planets all formed around the same star and from the same protoplanetary disk.  Furthermore, the formation of ultra-short period planets (USPs), which are primarily rocky planets with orbital periods $<1 $ day, is poorly understood.  The NASA \TESS\ Mission has discovered TOI-561, a multi-planet system containing a USP.  This bright ($V=10.2$) star hosts three small transiting planet candidates: TOI-561 b (P=0.4 days, \rpl=1.6\,\rearth), c (P=10.8 days, \rpl= 3.2\,\rearth), and d (P=16.4 days, \rpl=2.8\,\rearth).  With radial velocities obtained on Keck/HIRES and [other facilities welcome], we confirm the planetary nature of all three candidates.  Planet b has \mpl= and \rhopl = , which are consistent with a rocky composition.  Planet c has \mpl= and \rhopl=, and planet d has \mpl= and \rhopl=), both of which are consistent with an interior rocky core overlaid with a low-mass volatile envelope.  The masses, radii, and orbits of the TOI-561 planets can be used to constrain the history of the system, and in particular to elucidate how the USP arrived at its present orbit.

Hi Lauren,

My preliminary modeling shows that our best estimates for Teff and L (from Gaia) are hard to reconcile with the measured [Fe/H] from Specmatch. I then noticed that TOI-561 has high Gaia proper motion:

PM_RA: -108.432 0.088
PM_DE: -61.511 0.094

Combining this with the Gaia RV makes the star kinematically consistent with the thick disc (see https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.07825). To confirm this, it'd be great to measure alpha-element abundances from the HIRES spectra. I can look into this, but it'd probably quicker and more reliable to ask John Brewer to run SME. If the star is indeed alpha-enhanced this would remove the discrepancy since it would enhance the bulk metallicity [M/H] (used by the interior models); it would be also be a nice spin on this system since there aren't many known multis around old, thick disc stars.

Title: The TESS Keck Survey I: Masses, Densities, and Orbits of Three Sub-Neptune Sized Transiting Planets in TOI-561
Authors: Lauren M. Weiss, Fei Dai, the TESS Keck Survey, and others

Abstract: Systems with multiple transiting planets provide excellent natural laboratories for testing the physics of planet formation, since the planets all formed around the same star and from the same protoplanetary disk.  Furthermore, the formation of ultra-short period planets (USPs), which are primarily rocky planets with orbital periods $<1 $ day, is poorly understood.  The NASA \TESS\ Mission has discovered TOI-561, a multi-planet system containing a USP.  This bright ($V=10.2$) star hosts three small transiting planet candidates: TOI-561 b (P=0.4 days, \rpl=1.6\,\rearth), c (P=10.8 days, \rpl= 3.2\,\rearth), and d (P=16.4 days, \rpl=2.8\,\rearth).  With radial velocities obtained on Keck/HIRES and [other facilities welcome], we confirm the planetary nature of all three candidates.  Planet b has \mpl= and \rhopl = , which are consistent with a rocky composition.  Planet c has \mpl= and \rhopl=, and planet d has \mpl= and \rhopl=), both of which are consistent with an interior rocky core overlaid with a low-mass volatile envelope.  The masses, radii, and orbits of the TOI-561 planets can be used to constrain the history of the system, and in particular to elucidate how the USP arrived at its present orbit.

Hi Lauren,

My preliminary modeling shows that our best estimates for Teff and L (from Gaia) are hard to reconcile with the measured [Fe/H] from Specmatch. I then noticed that TOI-561 has high Gaia proper motion:

PM_RA: -108.432 0.088
PM_DE: -61.511 0.094

Combining this with the Gaia RV makes the star kinematically consistent with the thick disc (see https://arxiv.org/abs/1911.07825). To confirm this, it'd be great to measure alpha-element abundances from the HIRES spectra. I can look into this, but it'd probably quicker and more reliable to ask John Brewer to run SME. If the star is indeed alpha-enhanced this would remove the discrepancy since it would enhance the bulk metallicity [M/H] (used by the interior models); it would be also be a nice spin on this system since there aren't many known multis around old, thick disc stars.

Summarizing some Slack discussion:
Howard notes: "CFOP working group SG2/4 just posted a note about TOI-1611 (CPS name= 207897). A Masters student from IAC in Spain, lead by Enric Palle will be writing it up using archival SOPHIE data. I think we should consider offering our HIRES data to their paper. This target to  far North(dec=~84), making it challenging to observe at Keck."
Andrew noted that it looks like a great target if the planet is real.  We should collect a few more RVs and contribute to Palle et al.  If the planet pans out, let's include it in TKS.

Ian noted that the SOPHIE team (apparently) sees the Doppler signal, giving confidence in the planet interpretation., Abstract of Heidari et al. (in prep.) posted to the MIT Spacebook:

We present the discovery and characterization of a transiting sub-Neptune-sized planet around TOI-1611 (also known as HD207897 or TIC 264678534), based on photometry and radial velocity measurements obtained by the short cadence of Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite (TESS) and SOPHIE high precision spectrograph. The host star is a bright (V=8.37) K0 dwarf which was continuously observed by TESS during sectors 18 and 19 while it was initially monitored in the context of the SOPHIE exoplanet consortium’s dedicate to explore of low-mass planets which obtained 44 high-resolution spectra over 3 years. By using the transit least squares (TLS) algorithm and considering the stellar host characteristics, we find that TOI-1611b is a mini- Neptune planet with radii of 2.2 R_Earth and orbits around its host star at a period of 16.2 days. We analyze the RV SOPHIE measurements, establish the planetary nature of this TESS candidate, and measure a planetary mass of 19.7 M_Earth. A simultaneous joint model of photometry and RVs data using two different packages, PASTIS and EXOFAST V2 in order to increase the precision of the planetary parameter is done., Abstract of Heidari et al. By using the transit least squares (TLS) algorithm and considering the stellar host characteristics, we find that TOI-1611b is a mini- Neptune planet with radii of 2.2 R_Earth and orbits around its host star at a period of 16.2 days. We analyze the RV SOPHIE measurements, establish the planetary nature of this TESS candidate, and measure a planetary mass of 19.7 M_Earth. comment_list:
Super-Earth with Msin i = 8.2 ± 1.2 M⊕ and P = 9.494 ± 0.005 days discovered by Howard et al. (2011) using Keck-HIRES RVs. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2011ApJ...730...10H/abstract, Henry et al. (2011) found transits of HD 97658 b using ground-based photometry from the Automated Photometric Telescope (APT)!!  Five partial transits were observed and all showed egress at 2-3.5 sigma significance.  Four other epoch were observed under similar conditions, when transits were not predicted, and transits were not detected!   Combining the five nights with predicted transits gave a 5.5-sigma detection with a transit depth of 1470 ± 260 ppm.  The four nights without transits were consistent with flat and gave a transit depth of 400 ± 398 ppm. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2011arXiv1109.2549H/abstract
However, this discovery was later shown to be wrong by follow-up observations by MOST and Spitzer. 
Note that the submission to ApJ of Henry et al. (2012) was withdrawn and the paper now only lives on arXiv., After the non-detection of transits of HD 97658b by MOST and Spitzer, the search continued.  Remarkably, both space telescopes discovered transits, but at a slightly different ephemeris (that is inconsistent with the transits from Henry et al. (2011)).  
Dragomir et al. (2013) found transits with MOST. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2013ApJ...772L...2D/abstract
Van Grootel et al. (2014) using Spitzer observations to confirm transits consistent with the MOST detection. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2014ApJ...786....2V/abstract, Knutson et al. (2014) measured the atmospheric transmission spectrum of this super-Earth in the 1.1-1.7um range using the WFC3 instrument on HST over two visits.  The spectrum appeared flat (perhaps due to clouds) and was inconsistent at the 10-sigma level with a solar-composition atmosphere (mostly H/He) having the expected scale height. https://ui.adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2014ApJ...794..155K/abstract, Stellar activity FP
